# Atlantis Test Framework

## Testing Library

- Atlantis uses Boost µTest (`boost::ut`) for unit testing
- Imported from `"external/boost/ut.hpp"`
- Namespace is typically aliased with `namespace ut = boost::ut;`

## Test Suite Structure

- Test suites are defined with named template parameters: `ut::suite<"SuiteName"> suite_name = []`
- Individual tests are defined using string literals with `_test` suffix: `"Test description"_test = []`
- Use test factory functions for reusable test patterns
- Test suite files should be named descriptively based on the functionality they test, ending with `_test.cpp`

## UnitTestHelper

- The `UnitTestHelper` class provides utilities for testing Atlantis code
- It captures stdout output from the game engine, allows access to private Game members, and provides shorthand for common operations
- Main test utilities:
  - `initialize_game()`: Sets up a minimal game environment
  - `set_skill_level()`: Sets a skill level, handling all prerequisites
  - `cout_data()`: Captures standard output from the game engine for verification
  - `create_faction()`, `create_unit()`, etc.: Helpers for creating test objects
  - `enable()`: Enable or disable items, skills, objects for testing
  - `activate_spell()`: Executes a specific spell directly

## Test Organization

- Related test cases should be grouped in the same suite
- Helper classes like `UnitTestHelper` should have their tests in a suite named after the helper class
- When testing multiple aspects of one feature, prefer multiple test cases in a single suite rather than multiple files
- Consolidate related tests in the same file even if they test different functions

## Assertions and Expectations

- Use the `expect` function for assertions: `expect(condition == value_i);`
- Numeric literals can be annotated with `_i` for integer comparisons
- Pointer validity can be checked with `expect(pointer != nullptr)`
- For common patterns, use utility functions to simplify tests

## Running Tests

- Tests are compiled with `make unittest`
- Execute all tests with `./unittest/unittest`
- Run specific test suites by passing the suite name: `./unittest/unittest SuiteName`
- All tests should be independent and not rely on state from other tests

# Atlantis Test Framework Standards

## General Principles
- Tests should be isolated and not depend on side effects from other tests
- Each test should focus on one specific behavior or feature
- Use descriptive test names that explain the expected behavior
- Example: `"CAST TRANSMUTATION parses and executes correctly"_test`

## Test Helper Framework
- Use the appropriate test helper methods for specific testing scenarios
- Use `helper.setup_turn()` to prepare the game state before testing
- Use `helper.parse_orders()` to process orders from a string stream
- For spells, use `activate_spell()` instead of `run_month_orders()`
- Example:
  ```cpp
  helper.activate_spell(S_TRANSMUTATION, {
      .region = region, .unit = unit, .object = nullptr, .val1 = 0, .val2 = 0
  });
  ```

## Game Configuration
- Set appropriate global flags in unittest/rules.cpp
- Enable required game elements for your test:
  ```cpp
  helper.enable(UnitTestHelper::Type::ITEM, I_SWORD, true);
  helper.enable(UnitTestHelper::Type::SKILL, S_PATTERN, true);
  ```
- Set up units with proper skill levels:
  ```cpp
  helper.set_skill_level(unit, S_TRANSMUTATION, 3);
  ```

## Error Testing
- Validate exact error messages, including case sensitivity:
  ```cpp
  expect(faction->errors.size() == 1);
  expect(faction->errors[0].message == "CAST 'transmutation': You must specify what you wish to create.");
  ```
- Check that no side effects occurred:
  ```cpp
  expect(unit->items.GetNum(I_IRON) == 1); // Item not consumed
  expect(unit->items.GetNum(I_MITHRIL) == 0); // No product created
  ```

## System Integration Testing
- Account for faction knowledge requirements:
  ```cpp
  faction->DiscoverItem(I_IRON, 1, 1);
  faction->DiscoverItem(I_MITHRIL, 1, 1);
  ```
- Set up prerequisites for powers and skills
- Test interactions between connected systems (items, spells, faction knowledge)

## Command Testing
- Test different input formats for commands:
  ```cpp
  ss << "ARMOR \"chain armor\" plate_armor\n"; // Both quoted and underscore styles
  ```
- Know item categorization (weapons vs. armor vs. battle items)
- Verify order processing correctly affects game state:
  ```cpp
  expect(unit->readyWeapon[0] == I_SWORD);
  expect(unit->readyWeapon[1] == I_LONGBOW);
  ```

## Test Coverage
- Include both success and failure tests for each command
- Test edge cases like missing parameters, invalid items
- Test specific error conditions and verify proper error handling

## Code Quality
- Remove unnecessary variables when refactoring:
  ```cpp
  // Before
  ARegion *region = unit->object->region; // Unused in this test

  // After
  // Variable removed
  ```
- Use compact initializers when appropriate:
  ```cpp
  // Before multi-line
  helper.activate_spell(S_TRANSMUTATION, {
      .region = region,
      .unit = unit,
      .object = nullptr,
      .val1 = 0,
      .val2 = 0
  });

  // After single-line when simple
  helper.activate_spell(S_TRANSMUTATION, {.region = region, .unit = unit, .object = nullptr, .val1 = 0, .val2 = 0});
  ```
